cor_data=data.frame(cbind(alldata$touristnumber,alldata$Income,alldata$SearchforTurkey,alldata$SearchofHotelsinTurkey)) 
colnames(cor_data)=c("TouristNumber", "TravelIncome", "GoogleSearchforTurkey","GoogleSearchofHotelsinTurkey") 

ggcorrplot(cor(cor_data), 
           hc.order = TRUE, 
           type = "lower",
           lab = TRUE)

When the ggpair and ggcorplot tables are examined, it seems that all of the categories are correlated with the search of "Hotel" in Turkey. In order to explain deeply, i will try to clarify all relations independently.

Search for Turkey in World vs Search for Hotels in Turkey: Their correlation coefficient is 0.827 which is the highest coefficient among them. Scatter plot of them shows that the seasonality effects both of them in a similar way. It is reasonable beacuse Turkey is a country where people would take vacation in the summer generally. When people search "Turkey" in google and decide to come here, they search hotels to stay during their vacation.

Total Travel Income vs Search for Hotels in Turkey: Correlation coefficient between total travel income and search for "Hotel" in Turkey is 0.573. Despite the fact that it is a strong correlation, it is the lowest correlation coefficent among them. When we look at the comparison scatter plot, the pattern of total travel income seems to have shifted a little more to the right from the pattern of search data for "Hotel". The reason behind this may be that people actually come to Turkey on holiday after a while after making their search.

Number of Tourists in Turkey vs Search for Hotels in Turkey: The correlation coefficient between them is 0.655. It is stronger relation than Total Travel Income vs Search for Hotels in Turkey. However their pattern looks similar to Income vs Search for Hotels. The reason that makes their relation stronger than the Income vs Search for Hotels may be that everyone who come to Turkey need to find a place to stay, but they do not have to spend a lot of money.

5) Conclusion¶

To conculude, I try to investigate relations Google search of "Hotel" in Turkey with number of tourists in Turkey, total travel income of Turkey and Google search of "Turkey" in World. The observations from scatter plots, it can be seen that They all have similar seasonal patterns.In addittion to that, the data which the ggpair and ggcorplot tables give shows us the correlations are very high. From the plots of ggpairs, It can be said that there are linear relations between search for "Hotel" and others.
